Insertion Sort is a simple, comparison-based sorting algorithm that works the same way you sort playing cards in your hand.
It builds the sorted list one element at a time by inserting each new element into its correct position in the already sorted part.

Steps:
  Assume the first element is already sorted.
  Take the next element (called the key).
  Compare the key with elements in the sorted part (to its left).
  Shift all elements that are greater than the key one position to the right.
  Insert the key in its correct position.
  Repeat until all elements are sorted.

Key Characteristics
  Time Complexity
    Best case: O(n) (already sorted)
    Average case: O(n²)
    Worst case: O(n²) (reverse sorted)
  Space Complexity
    O(1) (in-place)
  Stability
    ✅ Stable (preserves order of equal elements)
  Adaptiveness
    ✅ Adaptive (efficient for nearly sorted arrays)

  When to use Insertion Sort
    ✅ Good for:
      Small datasets
      Nearly sorted arrays
      Online sorting (elements arrive one by one)
    ❌ Not suitable for:
      Large datasets

